DERVAUX Gautier - 1971606
MENGHETTI Marina -1971617

Project Description¶

Taken from 2018 Kagle competition, our project goal is to predict whether a user will listen again to song in the 30 days after they first listened to it.
We have different datasets that come from KKBox an asian leader of music streaming. First, the ratings themselves, with the user_id and song_id as well with the context of their first listen. Moreover we have for every song: its duration, language, genre and others. We also have information on the users (called members): their gender, the time of subscription, their city etc. As an evaluation metric, the kaggle compeition focuses on the Area Under the Curve of the ROC curve. To be able to compare with the competition's leaderboard, we decided to use the same metrics to compare our different models. In order to be able to compute the ROC curve, we will predict a probability for the user to listen again the song during the month following the first listen. The threshold to predict the positive/negative class will be changed, in order to compute the different points of our ROC curve. Our report is organised likewise:

  1. Data exploartion
  2. Preparing the data
  3. Baseline
  4. The item-item approach
  5. The Collaborative Deep learning with and without context
  6. Conclusion and possible improvements

The dataset is very big. We have informations on a lot of songs and users that don't necessarily have votes. More importantly, the ratings distribution is very unequal. The median number of votes per item is 2 whereas users have a median of more than a 100 votes. However, there is still many users with very few votes. This is a typical cold start problem. That's why we decided to use hybrid techniques that uses both the content information to handle those users and items, and the collaborative informations such as ratings.

Content information's influence on the ratings¶

In [0]:
def studyAttribute(train, attribute, plot=True, typeAttr=str):
  attributeValues = train[attribute].unique()
  ratios = [np.mean(train[ (train[attribute]==value) if type(value) is typeAttr or (type(value) is not float and not math.isnan(value)) else (train[attribute].isna())].target) for value in attributeValues ]
  if(plot):
    plt.figure(figsize=(10,5))
    plt.barh(range(len(attributeValues)), ratios)
    plt.yticks(range(len(attributeValues)),attributeValues)
  return attributeValues, ratios

def studyContinousAttribute(train, attribute, num_bucket=10, plot=True, log=True):
  min_val, max_val = min(train[attribute]), max(train[attribute])
  new_attr = attribute+"_discrete"
  attributeValues = train[attribute]
  if log:
    l = np.logspace(np.log10(min_val),np.log10(max_val),num=num_bucket)
    train[new_attr] = attributeValues.apply(lambda el: bisect(l, el))
  else:
    train[new_attr] = attributeValues.apply(lambda el: el//((max_val-min_val)/num_bucket))
  
  attributeValues, ratios = studyAttribute(train, new_attr, plot=False, typeAttr=np.float64)
  res_df = pd.DataFrame({"attributeValues":attributeValues,"ratios":ratios})
  res_df = res_df.sort_values(by='attributeValues')
  if(plot):
    plt.figure(figsize=(10,5))
    plt.scatter(res_df.attributeValues,res_df.ratios)
    ax = plt.gca()
    if log:
      ax.set_xticklabels(10**res_df.attributeValues)
    else:
      ax.set_xticklabels(np.linspace(min_val,max_val,num_bucket))

  return attributeValues, ratios

As we expected, not all attributes seem to have a significant impact on the ratings. The gender doesn't really have an influence as we can see. The context, on the other hand, seem to have a great impact. It's quite reasonable that users are more likely to listen again to a song in their library, than one they listened on the radio. Indeed, if you listen a song on the radio, it's not always a song you like, and even if you like the song, you could not be able to find the song again in order to listen again to it.
However this is a simple study. The gender coupled with other factors can bring more information.

Preparing Data¶

As previously seen, the amount of data is larger than the ones from the labs and can lead to very long computation time. That's why we decided to train our models on a subset of the data: the first 10% of the ratings.
To really measure our models' performances, we also extracted from the train a validation set. We'll train on the first set and evaluate the performance by predicting the ratings in the validation set, and comparing with the actual ratings.
It's important to note that we take those two sets consecutively because the kaggle competition clearly states that the test data the teams had to predict is data that happened after the train in a timely fashion. The listens being ordered as well, taking consecutive sets and not random ones gives a better sense of the performance on the actual test dataset.

def evaluateModel(predictions, ground_truth, plot=True, label=None, title=None):
    fpr,tpr,_= roc_curve(ground_truth,predictions)
    auc_score = auc(fpr,tpr)
    if(plot):
        plt.plot(fpr,tpr,label="AUC:"+str(np.round(auc_score,2))+" "+label)
        plt.xlabel('False Positive Rate',size=axis_label_size)
        plt.ylabel('True Positive Rate',size=axis_label_size)
        plt.title(title, size=title_size)
        plt.legend()
    return auc_score, fpr, tpr

def perf_for_n_vote(test_u, test_i, test_label, num_vote_per_user, model, n_vote=0, lower_n_vote=0, context=None):
  test_index_n = list(filter(lambda x: x is not None,[i if num_vote_per_user[u]<=n_vote and num_vote_per_user[u]>=lower_n_vote else None for i,u in enumerate(test_u)]))
  
  test_u_n, test_i_n, test_label_n = test_u[test_index_n], test_i[test_index_n], test_label[test_index_n]
  if context is not None:
    context_n = context[test_index_n]
    test_label_n = test_label[test_index_n]
    predictions = model.predict(test_u_n, test_i_n, context_n, test_label_n)
  else:
    predictions = model.predict(test_u_n, test_i_n)
  auc,_,_ = evaluateModel(predictions, test_label_n, label="{}".format(model.name), title='Users between {} and {} votes in training data'.format(lower_n_vote,n_vote))
  return auc

class Baseline:
    def __init__(self, name, user_mean=True, item_mean=True):
      self.name = name
      self.user_mean = user_mean
      self.item_mean = item_mean
      return

    def predict(self, user_indeces, song_indeces):
      predictions = []
      for user_index,song_index in zip(user_indeces,song_indeces):
        user_mean = 0.5
        if self.user_mean and len(users_votes[user_index])>0:
          user_mean = np.mean(users_votes[user_index])
        
        item_mean = 0.5
        if self.item_mean and len(items_votes[song_index])>0:
          item_mean = np.mean(items_votes[song_index])
        
        predictions.append((user_mean+item_mean)/2)
      return predictions

Item Item¶

In [0]:
from sklearn.metrics.pairwise import cosine_similarity
from sklearn.metrics import mean_squared_error

class ItemItem:
    
    def __init__(self, K, name, metric = cosine_similarity):
        self.K = K #Number of neighbour
        self.simi_metric = cosine_similarity
        self.songNeigboursCos = {} #Keep neighbours cos similarity to speed predictions after train
        self.name = name
        
    def predict_one(self, user_index, song_index):
        
      if len(items_votes[song_index])==0:
        return 0
    
      if song_index not in self.songNeigboursCos:
          song_vector = vote_matrix[:,song_index]
          song_cos_simi = self.simi_metric(np.transpose(vote_matrix),np.transpose(song_vector))

          song_neigbours  = song_cos_simi.reshape((len(song_cos_simi),)).argsort()[-self.K-1:-1][::-1]
          song_neigbours_cos = song_cos_simi[song_neigbours].reshape((self.K,))
          self.songNeigboursCos[song_index] = (song_neigbours_cos,song_neigbours)
      else: 
          (song_neigbours_cos,song_neigbours) = self.songNeigboursCos[song_index]
            
      _, non_zero_neighbour, non_zero_neighbour_targets = find(vote_matrix[user_index,song_neigbours])
      
      if len(non_zero_neighbour_targets)==0 or sum(song_neigbours_cos[non_zero_neighbour])==0:
        return 0.5
    
      non_zero_neighbour_cos = song_neigbours_cos[non_zero_neighbour]/sum(song_neigbours_cos[non_zero_neighbour])
      pred = (np.dot(non_zero_neighbour_cos,non_zero_neighbour_targets)+1)/2
      return pred

    def predict(self, batch_user_index , batch_song_index, print_progress=False):
        predictions_itemitem = []
        n = 0
        
        for u,i in zip(batch_user_index,batch_song_index):
          prediction = self.predict_one(u,i)
          predictions_itemitem.append(prediction)
          if print_progress:
            n+=1
            print(n/len(batch_user_index)*100)
            
        return predictions_itemitem

As the figures above show, the item item approach does not improve the baseline. Even with 1000 neighbours which gave the best results, the model struggles a lot with cold start user wich is not surprising. However even with more ratings, the approach still underperforms the baseline.
To solve this cold start issue, one needs to add data about the user or the item, or both.

Collaborative Deep Learning¶

Inspired by https://github.com/ChenBoSyun/implement-Collaborative-Deep-Learning-for-Recommender-Systems/blob/master/CDL_tf.ipynb and https://www.pyimagesearch.com/2018/06/04/keras-multiple-outputs-and-multiple-losses/ and https://github.com/zoujun123/Keras-CDL/blob/master/CDL.py

As our data exploring pointed out, the content information can add very precious information on the target. To use that, we decided to implement the Collaborative Deep Learning approach Gautier presented in class. The model presented only takes into account item content information, but in this problem, the context seems also important. Therefore we tried two architectures, one similar to the one by the authors and a modified version with the context. The schemas are from the presentation we did.

The Vanilla version from the paper¶

The version with a context added¶

class BatchGenerator(Sequence):
    def __init__(self, users, items, ratings, context, batch_size, item_mat):
        self.users, self.context, self.items, self.ratings = users, context, items, ratings
        self.batch_size = batch_size
        self.item_mat = item_mat

    def __len__(self):
        return len(self.users)//self.batch_size+1

    def __getitem__(self, idx):
    
        user = self.users[idx*self.batch_size:(idx+1)*self.batch_size]
        items = self.items[idx*self.batch_size:(idx+1)*self.batch_size]
        item_feat = np.array([self.item_mat[items[x]] for x in range(items.shape[0])])
        
        ratings = self.ratings[idx*self.batch_size:(idx+1)*self.batch_size]
        
        if self.context is not None:
          context = self.context[idx*self.batch_size:(idx+1)*self.batch_size]       
          return([user.reshape((len(user),-1)), context, items.reshape((len(user),-1)), item_feat],[ratings.reshape((len(user),-1)), item_feat])
        else:
          return([user.reshape((len(user),-1)), items.reshape((len(user),-1)), item_feat],[ratings.reshape((len(user),-1)), item_feat])

class CollaborativeDeepLearning:
  def __init__(self, item_mat, hidden_layers, name='CDL', context=True):
    '''
    hidden_layers = a list of three integer indicating the embedding dimension of autoencoder
    item_mat = item feature matrix with shape (# of item, # of item features)
    '''
    assert(len(hidden_layers)==3)
    self.item_mat = item_mat
    self.hidden_layers = hidden_layers
    self.item_dim = hidden_layers[0]
    self.embedding_dim = hidden_layers[-1]
    self.name = name
    self.history = None
    self.context = context
    
  def pretrain(self, lamda_w=0.1, encoder_noise=0.1, dropout_rate=0.1, activation='sigmoid', batch_size=64, epochs=10):
    '''
    layer-wise pretraining on item features (item_mat)
    '''
    self.trained_encoders = []
    self.trained_decoders = []
    X_train = self.item_mat
    layer_index = 0
    
    for input_dim, hidden_dim in zip(self.hidden_layers[:-1], self.hidden_layers[1:]):
      print('Pretraining the layer: Input dim {} -> Output dim {}'.format(input_dim, hidden_dim))
      pretrain_input = tf.keras.layers.Input(shape=(input_dim,))
      encoded = tf.keras.layers.GaussianNoise(stddev=encoder_noise)(pretrain_input)
      encoded = tf.keras.layers.Dropout(dropout_rate)(encoded)
      encoder = tf.keras.layers.Dense(hidden_dim, activation=activation, kernel_regularizer=l2(lamda_w), bias_regularizer=l2(lamda_w))(encoded)
      decoder = tf.keras.layers.Dense(input_dim, activation=activation, kernel_regularizer=l2(lamda_w), bias_regularizer=l2(lamda_w))(encoder)
      # autoencoder
      ae = tf.keras.models.Model(inputs=pretrain_input, outputs=decoder)
      # encoder
      ae_encoder = tf.keras.models.Model(inputs=pretrain_input, outputs=encoder)
      # decoder
      encoded_input = tf.keras.layers.Input(shape=(hidden_dim,))
      decoder_layer = ae.layers[-1] # the last layer
      ae_decoder = tf.keras.models.Model(encoded_input, decoder_layer(encoded_input))

      ae.compile(loss='mse', optimizer='adam')
      ae.fit(X_train, X_train, batch_size=batch_size, epochs=epochs, verbose=2)

      self.trained_encoders.append(ae_encoder)
      self.trained_decoders.append(ae_decoder)
      X_train = ae_encoder.predict(X_train)
  
  def buildFullModel(self, train_mat, test_mat, lamda_u=0.1, lamda_v=0.1, lamda_n=0.1, lr=0.001):
    '''
    Fine-tuning with rating prediction
    '''
    train_u, train_i, train_label, train_context = train_mat
    test_u, test_i, test_label, test_context = test_mat
    num_user = int( max(train_u.max(),test_u.max()) + 1 )
    num_item = int( max(train_i.max(),test_i.max()) + 1 )
    print("num user {} num item {}".format(num_user,num_item))

    # item autoencoder 
    itemfeat_InputLayer = tf.keras.layers.Input(shape=(self.item_dim,), name='item_feat_input')
    encoded = self.trained_encoders[0](itemfeat_InputLayer)
    encoded = self.trained_encoders[1](encoded)
    decoded = self.trained_decoders[1](encoded)
    decoded = self.trained_decoders[0](decoded)

    # user embedding
    user_InputLayer = tf.keras.layers.Input(shape=(1,), dtype='int32', name='user_input')
    user_EmbeddingLayer = tf.keras.layers.Embedding(input_dim=num_user, output_dim=self.embedding_dim, input_length=1, name='user_embedding', embeddings_regularizer=l2(lamda_u), 
                                    embeddings_initializer=RandomNormal(mean=0, stddev=1))(user_InputLayer)
    user_EmbeddingLayer = tf.keras.layers.Flatten(name='user_flatten')(user_EmbeddingLayer)

    # item embedding
    item_InputLayer = tf.keras.layers.Input(shape=(1,), dtype='int32', name='item_input')
    item_OffsetVector = tf.keras.layers.Embedding(input_dim=num_item, output_dim=self.embedding_dim, input_length=1, name='item_offset_vector', embeddings_regularizer=l2(lamda_v), 
                                  embeddings_initializer=RandomNormal(mean=0, stddev=1))(item_InputLayer)
    item_OffsetVector = tf.keras.layers.Flatten(name='item_flatten')(item_OffsetVector)
    item_EmbeddingLayer = tf.keras.layers.Add()([encoded, item_OffsetVector]) 
    
    if self.context:
      # context embedding
      context_InputLayer = tf.keras.layers.Input(shape=(train_context.shape[1],), name='context_input')
      context_dim_reductions = tf.keras.layers.Dense(self.embedding_dim, activation=K.relu)(context_InputLayer)
      
      context_user = tf.keras.layers.Add()([context_dim_reductions, user_EmbeddingLayer]) 
      
      # rating prediction
      dotLayer = tf.keras.layers.Dot(axes = -1)([context_user, item_EmbeddingLayer])
      dotLayer = tf.keras.layers.Activation('tanh',name='dot_layer')(dotLayer)

      self.cdl_model = tf.keras.models.Model(inputs=[user_InputLayer, context_InputLayer, item_InputLayer, itemfeat_InputLayer], outputs=[dotLayer, decoded])
    else:
      # rating prediction
      dotLayer = tf.keras.layers.Dot(axes = -1)([user_EmbeddingLayer, item_EmbeddingLayer])
      dotLayer = tf.keras.layers.Activation('tanh',name='dot_layer')(dotLayer)

      self.cdl_model = tf.keras.models.Model(inputs=[user_InputLayer, item_InputLayer, itemfeat_InputLayer], outputs=[dotLayer, decoded])

    self.cdl_model.compile(optimizer='adam', loss=['mse', 'mse'], loss_weights=[1, lamda_n])
  
  def train(self, train_mat, test_mat, batch_size=64, epochs=10):

    train_u, train_i, train_label, train_context = train_mat
    test_u, test_i, test_label, test_context = test_mat
    
    if not self.context:
      train_context, test_context = None, None
    
    train_generator = BatchGenerator(train_u, train_i, train_label, train_context, batch_size, self.item_mat)
    test_generator = BatchGenerator(test_u, test_i, test_label, test_context, batch_size, self.item_mat)

    model_history = self.cdl_model.fit_generator(generator=train_generator,
                                                validation_data=test_generator,
                                                use_multiprocessing=True,
                                                workers=4,
                                                epochs=epochs)
    if self.history is None:
      self.history = model_history
    else:
      max_previous_epoch = max(self.history.epoch)
      self.history.epoch += list(range(max_previous_epoch+1,max_previous_epoch+epochs+1))
      for key in self.history.history:
        self.history.history[key] += model_history.history[key]
        
    return model_history
      
  def getRMSE(self, test_mat, print_auc=True, label="CDL test"):

    test_u, test_i, test_label, test_context = test_mat
    predictions = self.predict(test_u, test_i, test_context, test_label)
    if(print_auc):
        evaluateModel((np.array(predictions)+1)/2,(np.array(test_label)+1)/2, plot=True, label=label)
    return np.sqrt(np.mean(np.square(np.array(test_label) - np.array(predictions))))
  
  def predict(self, u, i, context, label):
    batch_size = 256
    
    if not self.context:
      context = None
    
    generator = BatchGenerator(u, i, label, context, batch_size, self.item_mat)
    predictions = []
    
    for i in range(generator.__len__()):
      if self.context:
        [u, context, item, item_feat], [label, item_feat] = generator.__getitem__(i)
        [pred_out, decoded_out] = self.cdl_model.predict([u, context, item, item_feat])
      else:
        [u, item, item_feat], [label, item_feat] = generator.__getitem__(i)
        [pred_out, decoded_out] = self.cdl_model.predict([u, item, item_feat])
      predictions += list(pred_out.flatten())
    
    return predictions
  
  def printAuc(self, test_mat, plot_label="CDL"):
    test_u, test_i, test_label, test_context = test_mat
    pred_test = self.predict(test_u, test_i, test_context, test_label)
    auc_score_test, _, _ = evaluateModel(pred_test, test_label, label=plot_label)
    # plt.show()
    return auc_score_test

One can observe that the CDL method without any context does not improve the baseline. But with the context information, we actually improve the baseline! Especially, when focusing with cold start user, the CDL with context achieves a 0.66 compared to the 0.6 auc of the baseline. Our first hint on the context data is confirmed.

Conclusion and Possible Improvements¶

In conclusion, this competition was really interesting and quite complex. The sparsity of the vote_matrix due to its size is a tough problem to solve. Collaborative data alone is not powerful enough to make good predictions, but not all content information have the same impact on the performance.
There is still a lot of room for improvement on our system. We could first improve the representation of the song. For exemple, some songs can have two different genre but here we considered it as a different one. We could include more information on the songs like the popularity of the artists for instance or the name of the songs.
We could also explore more the parameters of the CDL like the reconstruction objectif weigh or the noise parameters.
We also thought about different architectures that take the user informations as well as the context. We could introduce a second reconstruction objectif on them as well.

Future work: addition of user information in the architecture¶

Future work: addition of a second reconstruction objective for the representation of "a user in a specific context"¶

What was especially interesting in this project was the information about the context. Usually we have information about item and users, and the ratings. But in this project we have informations about ratings themselves. We didn't see in the course how to use this type of information, and using it with an architecture that makes sense was a challenge.
